<br>
What a minstrel can do is very limited, HOWEVER what they can do is very effective and replaced by very few other classes.<br>
<br>
It's important to note, that I cannot be in active combat and play songs at the same time.  In other words, I can not manage a heal song and slash a mob.<br>
<br>
Okay what can I do:<br>
<br>
Play a Heal Song throughout your combat.  Right now I cannot provide how much I heal per tick.  Hopefully some day.<br>
(requires lute)<br>
<br>
Play a Power Song throughout your combat.  Meaning I can replace your power 'mana' throughout your combat.  Most healer types will request I play this in most cases.<br>
(requires drum)<br>
<br>
Play a Speed Song in order for us to get from point A to point B.  Many times this saves 5sp for short journies.<br>
(requires drum)<br>
<br>
Play a Mez Song when there are two or more mobs incoming.  How do you know if mob is mezzed, well a green aura surrounds it.  Think of a minstrel as an enchanter from EQ, they need a clear line of sight on incoming mobs in order to mez one.<br>
(requires flute)<br>
<br>
Play a Charm Song on Humanoids.  Charming one mob to bash on another, though I am restricted to most human looking creatures.<br>
(requires flute)<br>
<br>
I can use slashing weapons and thrusting weapons, as well as anyone else.<br>
<br>
Now whether I am playing a song or I am in combat, I can also do the following things at any given time, though restricted how often I can do them.<br>
<br>
I can Stun incoming mobs to give the puller a few seconds to recover and set-up.  <br>
<br>
I can do Direct Damage by shouting at them for damage with two different songs, which I space apart.<br>
<br>
I can Confuse the mob.  This is one that seems to puzzle most as to why I use it.  If I see a mob truly smacking the crap out of one player, I know from experience one healer will have trouble keeping up, so I will confuse the mob.  If the mob attacks the healer, I will confuse it.  If the mob attacks me, I will confuse it.  A rezzer with a minstrel providing speed beside them avoids TPW.  So for all you melee who all of a sudden have to start chasing this ping-pong mob around, understand sometimes it's a necessity.<br>
<br>
DAoC does not allow us to 'twist', as well switching from weapon to instrument is relatively easy with hotkeys.  Switching from instrument to instrument is not, as you MUST have inventory open.  An instrument requires two hands at all times.<br>
<br>
Well there you have it.  A full explanation as to why a Minstrel is an important part of any group makeup.<br>
